   <abstract >This dissertation seeks to contextualize Cassius Dio as a Second Sophistic author and historian, and to demonstrate his use of Plato's political philosophy as a rubric by which to evaluate the government of the contemporary Roman Empire that he helped to administer. To do this, in Chapter 1 I first review the current state of Dio scholarship. Next, I propose an intertextual methodology to establish Dio's reference to Plato, noting that reference to Plato is a common historiographical technique. Chapter 2 reconstructs elite education in the late 2nd century CE. This reconstruction, along with a few definitions of terms indicate a heavy use of Plato's Republic as an essential educational text. Chapter 3 reviews the state of political philosophy as conceived by the four major philosophical schools of Roman antiquity, concentrating on the "Middle Platonic" philosophy of Dio's own time. This chapter demonstrates a heavy debt by the other schools to Plato's, including notions of the ideal constitution. Chapter 4 focuses on the figure of Plato's philosopher-king from the Republic. The last chapter deals with Platonic references in the speeches of the Augustan books. I conclude with a discussion of further lines of inquiry into the relationship between Plato and Dio, including his use of the tyrant from book 9 of the Republic as a paradigm for those negative imperial portraits found in the History.</abstract>
